lg.l:
Do not enter the city, O mountain with the ten strengths who has accomplished his
                journey!” The Tib. reads,
                “O you who have accomplished the ten strengths.” {4.9}

Give comfort, O supreme being, to all those who draw breath. The Skt. phrase “Give comfort . . . to all
                those who draw breath” involves a play on words, as the Skt. āśvāsaya (“give them comfort”) literally
                means “make them breathe freely.” {4.19}

Along with the bodhisattvas with great magical powers. In the Tib., possibly reflecting a
                different Skt. reading, this verse is, “I will summon them by a great
                miracle.” {4.57}

div.p:
The great sage, holding a flower The phrase “holding a flower” has been
              supplied from the Tib. (Skt. lacuna). in his folded hands, then praised the
            Blessed One with the following verses: {K103}

lg.l:
May all beings attain the bliss of the buddhas and find lasting nirvāṇa. The translation of this verse
                is partially based on the Tib., as the Skt. text includes a number of
                lacunae. {4.112}

May they obtain wisdom and sound sense faculties! The Tib. reads, “May they attain the
                wisdom of the essential nature that is endowed with the quintessence of the sense
                faculties.” {TK124}

For eons I will purify buddha fields, wisdom, and the ocean of beings. The translation of this verse
                is partially based on the Tib., as the Skt. text includes a number of
                lacunae. {4.117}

O leader with your unimpeded wisdom and omniscience, please make my prophesy! The translation of this verse
                is partially based on the Tib., as the Skt. text includes a number of
                lacunae. {4.118}

With a fivefold noose!”
                The phrase “fivefold noose” has been supplied from the Tib. (Skt. lacuna).
              {5.8}

How it should be fostered.
                Reading puṣpa˚ (“flowers”) as puṣya˚ (“to be fostered”), against the Tib. reading,
                which reflects puṣpa˚. {5.14} {TK143}

Those who know this will be free from fever;
                Jvara (“fever”) is used here in the sense of
                mental anguish.

